snippet.textDisplay:
So after a little snooping into Russia's copyright laws, mainly the copyright law of 1993 (I wont bore you all with legalize but I will tell you this law in particular matters)
The rights of an author are: ... [The right to the integrity of the work protects an author's works from distortions or other modifications that would be deemed detrimental to the author's reputation.] Distortions or other modifications, includes changes and eraser. But that isn't the only violation of this law, The right to disclosure of the work. [Disclosure again has the broad meaning of making the work accessible to the general public with the consent of the author through publication, public display, performance, broadcast, or other means.] Publication is the distribution of copies of a work to the general public with the author's consent.
Not to mention Russia has a funny little addendum to their copyright and trademark laws, Russia recognizes both moral rights and economic rights.
Moral rights are what's important here and include that whole, "Author consent" thing
Huge miss step on this dude's part and more then enough for official inquiry into the case, not to mention some international agreements on content on the internet Russia signed in 2018
Isn't Copyright law fun!
